SIMPLE: etch
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Etch
<hw>Etch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A variant of
<er>Eddish</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Etch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Etch
<hw>Etch</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Etched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Etching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[D. <ets>etsen</ets>, G.
<ets>⟦aum⟧tzen</ets> to feed, corrode, etch. MHG. <ets>etzen</ets>,
causative of <ets>ezzen</ets> to eat, G. <ets>essen</ets> <?/<?/. See
<er>Eat</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To produce, as figures or designs,
on mental, glass, or the like, by means of lines or strokes eaten in or
corroded by means of some strong acid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The plate is first covered with varnish, or some other
ground capable of resisting the acid, and this is then scored or
scratched with a needle, or similar instrument, so as to form the
drawing; the plate is then covered with acid, which corrodes the metal
in the lines thus laid bare.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To subject to etching; to draw upon and bite with
acid, as a plate of metal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I was <qex>etching</qex> a plate at the beginning of 1875.</q>
<rj><qau>Hamerton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To sketch; to delineate.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There are many empty terms to be found in some learned writes, to
which they had recourse to <qex>etch</qex> out their system.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Etch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Etch
<hw>Etch</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To practice etching; to make
etchings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>etched</ent>⟦br⟧
